    bio: 'Hannah Arendt was born in Linden, Germany (now part of Hanover), into a secular Jewish family of Russian origin. She studied philosophy at the University of Marburg under Martin Heidegger, with whom she had a brief but intellectually formative romantic relationship, before completing her doctorate under Karl Jaspers at the University of Heidelberg in 1929 with a dissertation on the concept of love in Saint Augustine. The rise of Nazism forced her to flee Germany in 1933; she lived as a stateless refugee in France before emigrating to the United States in 1941, where she became a citizen in 1951 and established herself as one of the most original political thinkers of the twentieth century.\n\nArendt\'s masterwork, "The Origins of Totalitarianism" (1951), traced the historical roots of Nazi and Soviet totalitarianism through imperialism, antisemitism, and the collapse of the nation-state system. Her subsequent work, "The Human Condition" (1958), offered a profound analysis of the active life — labor, work, and action — arguing that political action, the capacity to begin something genuinely new in concert with others, is the highest expression of human freedom. Her controversial report on the trial of Adolf Eichmann in Jerusalem, published as "Eichmann in Jerusalem: A Report on the Banality of Evil" (1963), introduced the concept of the "banality of evil" and sparked fierce debate about moral responsibility, obedience, and the nature of radical wickedness.\n\nThroughout her career, Arendt resisted easy categorization. She rejected the label "philosopher," preferring to call herself a political theorist, and she maintained a fierce independence from ideological camps of both left and right. Her later works, including "On Revolution" (1963) and the posthumously published "The Life of the Mind" (1978), explored the faculties of thinking, willing, and judging, seeking to understand how the inner life of the mind relates to moral and political action. Arendt died in New York City in 1975, leaving behind a body of work that continues to shape debates about democracy, freedom, authority, and the moral responsibilities of citizens in dark times.',
